{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"battle-of-hastings-1066","type":"event","content":{"title":"Battle of Hastings","date_label":"October 14, 1066","description":"The **Battle of Hastings** on October 14, 1066 was one of the most consequential engagements in English history. **William, Duke of Normandy** — claiming the English throne bequeathed to him by Edward the Confessor — defeated and killed **King Harold II**, the last Anglo-Saxon king of England.\n\nWilliam's Norman forces brought French language, feudal land organization, and continental ecclesiastical culture to England, fundamentally reshaping its society, legal system, and language. **Anglo-Norman French** became the language of the court and aristocracy; the fusion with Old English produced **Middle English** and eventually the modern English language.\n\nThe Norman Conquest also ended the Viking Age — the last serious Norse invasion attempt had been repelled by Harold at Stamford Bridge just weeks before Hastings, and the defeat of the Anglo-Saxons closed the era of Scandinavian political influence in Britain.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["battle","hastings","normans","william","harold","1066","england"],"sources":[{"title":"Battle of Hastings — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Battle-of-Hastings"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"1066","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":850,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"british-isles"}}}
